The third printing was invoiced in November 1871 and amounted to 20,640 stamps. This
was perforated 12\half and from a cover dated 17.7.72 we can now see that the colour was
bright violet. Probably the small printing of 28 sheets invoiced in May 1873 was in dull
purple.

I believe that only these two printings were perforated 12\half and that the printing in
February 1874 reverted to 14 perforation. My evidence is only circumstantial as dated
copies of these stamps are almost unknown and covers are scarce. We know however from
De La Rue records that 141,360 6d. stamps were invoiced in seven printings prior to the
reduction in price to Is. 4d. per 1,000 which took effect when the Crown Agents supplied
the paper which was watermarked C.C. We also know that stamps perforated 14 are much
commoner than those perforated 12\half. In my collection the rate is about 5 to 1 and if my
assumption that there were only two printings perforated 12\half is correct, we have figures
of 114,000 perforation 14 against 27,360 perforation 12Â£. I cannot in fact believe that there could be a much greater proportion of perforation 12 \half.


